#3-15 East 64th Street, North Side, between Fifth and Madison Avenues, showing the 5 story Orme Wilson, Jr. house, (#11), under construction. Between this and #3 lies #9, the property of E.P. Nichols which will shortly be demolished.

About 1900.

Photography by, Brown Bros.
108 Fulton Street,
Fifth Avenue at S.E. corner of 64th Street. Residence of James Ben Ali Higgin. About 1910.

834 and 835 Fifth Avenue, east side, between E. 64th and 65th Streets. Frank Gould is the owner of No. 834 and John W. Herbert of No. 835. The latter has been remodelled by Harry Allan Jacobs, Architect. F. Lewishon resided here until demolition in 1930 for the 15 story apartment house (No. 830), a structure that occupies this site and adjoining properties.

1910

Floyd E. Baker

14-18 East 64th Street, south side, between Fifth and Madison Avenues.

About 1922.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
824 to 827 Fifth Avenue, at S.E. corner of 64th Street. June, 1925.

Fifth Avenue, east side, 64th to 65th Streets. June 1925.
Houses are those of James Ben Ali Haggin (corner bldg), William Guggenheim, Frank Jay Gould, John W. Herbert, and Mrs. Isador Wormser.

title: Fifth Avenue - 64th Street, southeast corner

folder: 5th Avenue & Between 64th and 65th Streets, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Fifth Avenue, east side, south from East 65th (left) to 64th (right) Streets, as viewed from the 65th Street transverse road thru Central Park. These structures in 1925 were listed as the properties of the following individuals: Sophie A. Sherman (No. 837); Kate Bover (No. 836); F. Lewisohn (No. 835); A. S. Guggenheimer (No. 833); M. V. Hoggin (No. 830).

March 10, 1929

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
A northward view from East 64th Street, showing the site for a modern apartment house, (No. 830 Fifth Avenue) being prepared. This included the entire block front exclusive of the corner structures as shown. The corner house is the James Ben Ali Haggin mansion.

Aug. 15, 1929

P. L. Sperr.

(3)
A view similar to No. 1 but not as inclusive. Note the Sherman house at the S.E. corner of East 65th St. still standing.

April 23, 1938.

P. L. Sperr.
